Dataset was obtained from the UCI repo. The following is from its description:
The data is related with direct marketing campaigns of a Portuguese banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required, in order to access if the product (bank term deposit) would be (or not) subscribed.
The classification goal is to predict if the client will subscribe a term deposit (variable y).
Note: we have imbalanced classes.

Model Fitting¶

In [16]:
'''
'month' - missing months in dataset. encode them as jan = 1, feb = 2, etc
'contact' - telephone as 0, cellular as 1
'day_of_week' - encode mon as 1, tue as 2, etc
'education' - 8 uniques - basic.4y,high.school,basic.6y,basic.9y,professional.couse, unknown, university.degree, illiterate
encoding as: 
'unknown':0,'illiterate':1,'basic.4y':2,'basic.6y':3,'basic.9y':4,
                                           'high.school':5,'professional.course':6,'university.degree':7
'marital' - encoding as 'married':1,'divorced':1,'single':0,'unknown':0

'job' - encoding as 'retired','student': 1, others: 0
'''

def manual_encoders(df_in):
    month_enc = {'jan':1,'feb':2,'mar':3,'apr':4,'may':5,'jun':6,
                                   'jul':7,'aug':8,'sep':9,'oct':10,'nov':11,'dec':12}
    day_enc = {'mon':1,'tue':2,'wed':3,'thu':4,'fri':5}
    contact_enc = {'telephone':0,'cellular':1}
    education_enc = {'unknown':0,'illiterate':1,'basic.4y':2,'basic.6y':3,'basic.9y':4,
                                           'high.school':5,'professional.course':6,'university.degree':7}
    poutcome_enc = {'success':0.0,'failure':1.0,'nonexistent':0.5}
    
    df_in['month'] = df_in['month'].replace(month_enc)
    df_in['day_of_week'] = df_in['day_of_week'].replace(day_enc)
    df_in['contact'] = df_in['contact'].replace(contact_enc)
    df_in['education'] = df_in['education'].replace(education_enc)
    df_in['poutcome'] = df_in['poutcome'].replace(poutcome_enc)

    lhd_enc = {'no':0.0,'yes':1.0,'unknown':0.5} #encoder for loan, housing and default
    lhd_col = list(['loan','housing','default'])
    df_in[lhd_col] = df_in[lhd_col].replace(lhd_enc)
    
    marital_enc = {'married':1,'divorced':1,'single':0,'unknown':0}
    df_in['marital'] = df_in['marital'].replace(marital_enc)
    
    job_enc = {'admin.':0,'blue-collar':0,'technician':0,'services':0,'management':0,'retired':1,'entrepreneur':0,
           'self-employed':0,'housemaid':0,'unemployed':0,'student':1,'unknown':0}
    df_in['job'] = df_in['job'].replace(job_enc)
    
    y_enc = {'no':0,'yes':1}
    df_in['y'] = df_in['y'].replace(y_enc)
    
    return(df_in)   

df = manual_encoders(df)

classifiers = [SVC(kernel='rbf'),
               GaussianNB(),
               SGDClassifier(),
               LogisticRegression(),
               DecisionTreeClassifier(),
               XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False),
               LGBMClassifier(),

scores_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Classifier','TestRecall','TestAccuracy','TrainRecall','TrainAccuracy'])

for i in classifiers:
    i.fit(X_train,y_train)
    y_pred_test = i.predict(X_test)
    y_pred_train = i.predict(X_train)
    scores_df.loc[len(scores_df.index)] = [i.__class__.__name__,recall_score(y_test,y_pred_test),
                                           accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred_test),
                                           recall_score(y_train,y_pred_train),
                                           accuracy_score(y_train,y_pred_train)]

Model performance isn't stellar wrt to recall score, but it isn't abysmal either. Given the low fraction of 1s (~11%), I think performance of our workhorse classifiers (catboost, xgboost and lgbm) is pretty good. Let's use our old trick - upsample the minority class.

Up-sampling the Minority class¶

In [23]:
traindf = pd.concat([trainX,pd.DataFrame(y_train)],axis=1)

n0, n1 = traindf['y'].value_counts()

class0 = traindf[traindf['y'] == 0]
class1 = traindf[traindf['y'] == 1]
In [24]:
print("Before Resampling")
print("Fraction of class 1: {}".format(n1/(n0+n1)))

#we'll boost fraction of class 1 from ~11% to ~40%. 
#taking 6*n1 samples gives us ~44%

class1over = class1.sample(6*n1,replace=True)
overdf = pd.concat([class0,class1over],axis=0).sample(frac=1)

print("After Resampling")
print("Fraction of class 0: {}".format(overdf['y'].value_counts()[1]/overdf.shape[0]))
